        - <span>BUSINESS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Trad­ing house Mer­cu­ria and Sin­ga­pore-based as­set man­ager En­vy­s­ion Wealth Man­age­ment have agreed to co-in­vest in min­ing and en­ergy projects, as de­fault-hit banks tighten their purse strings and leave com­modi­ties firms seek­ing other fund­ing.</p>
    <p>The deal, signed on Wed­nes­day, will see Mer­cu­ria present po­ten­tial projects for in­vest­ment to En­vy­s­ion, founded and led by for­mer Julius Baer banker Veron­ica Shim. En­vy­s­ion will then de­cide whether to par­tic­i­pate via a fund with a start-up amount of US$100 mil­lion (S$132 mil­lion) to US$200 mil­lion.</p>


